Data Science Jobs Market

Backgroud


I propose the analysis of real job postings data gathered from Adzuna, a U.K based job search engine, which aggregates job postings from various different online sources. I want to use this data to: - Identify the different kinds of Data Science positions on offer in the U.K market, and the top skill sets for each. - Assign value to each skill based on position, company and Salary information (if available) - (potentially) Merge the jobs data with skills data from Universities and other institutions to understand skill gaps in the market This information will be very useful for program coordinators at Universities or skills academies and bootcamps (like the DataIncubator!), to offer students the skills which are actually being saught after in the job market.

```{r setup, include=FALSE}
library(flexdashboard)
library(ggplot2)
library(easyGgplot2)

df_data <- readRDS("df_data.rds")
top_words <- readRDS("top_words.rds")
skills_count <- readRDS("skills_count.rds")
category_tags <- readRDS("category_tags.rds")

### AESTHETICS
plot_col <- "darkblue"
plot_col_light <- "light blue"
theme_stripped <- theme(
  panel.background = element_blank(),
  axis.text = element_text(size = 12)
)
```


Backgroud {.sidebar}
=======================================================================



I propose the analysis of real job postings data gathered from Adzuna, a U.K based job search engine, which aggregates job postings from various different online sources. I want to use this data to:
 - Identify the different kinds of Data Science positions on offer in the U.K market, and the top skill sets for each.
 - Assign value to each skill based on position, company and Salary information (if available)
 - (potentially) Merge the jobs data with skills data from Universities and other institutions to understand skill gaps in the market
This information will be very useful for program coordinators at Universities or skills academies and bootcamps (like the DataIncubator!), to offer students the skills which are actually being saught after in the job market.

=======================================================================

### Salary Histogram

```{r, fig.width=12}
ggplot2.histogram(data=df_data, xName='mean_salary_thou', groupName='salary_is_predicted',legendPosition='right', groupColors = c(plot_col, plot_col_light), legendTitle="Salary\nType", xtitle="Salary (1000)") + theme_stripped

```

### Top words mentioned

```{r, fig.width=12}
ggplot(top_words[1:20, ], aes(x = reorder(word, count), y = count)) +
  geom_bar(fill = plot_col, stat = "identity") +
  ylab("") + xlab("") +
  coord_flip() +
  theme_stripped
```
